  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">PRRO 200447 Assistance to Address Food Insecurity and Under Nutrition</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed project addresses urgent nutritional needs of the refugees from Pakistan settled in Khost/Golam camp and the internal displaced persons (IDPs) settled in Kabul and in Herat. The primary target group are children 6 &#x2013; 59 months and pregnant and lactating women (PLW). Under the BSFP a total of 9,600 children and 4,800 PLW are expected to be assisted. Under TSFP in Hirat and Kabul a total of 33,100 children and 25,300 PLW will be reached with 2,308 MT of mixed food commodities: 86.4 Mt (Acha Mum), 297.9 MT (Wawa Mum) and 1,923.8 MT (Supercereal).  Acha Mum and Wawa Mum has as key ingredients: chickpeas, vegetable oil, milk powder, sugar, vitamins and minerals.  Acha is formulated for treatment of acute malnutrition, Wawa Mum is for prevention. The two RUSF will be procured from Pakistan while the supercereal (Corn/wheat/rice soya blend with sugar, vitamins and minerals) from Europe. The lead time to get these products in the country is in average three months. The BSFP and TSFP will be implemented by 3 National NGOs (ACTD, BDN and OHPM) and 1 International NGO (ACF). The activities will be run in close collaboration with other UN agencies, UNICEF, WHO, IOM UNHCR and MoPH/PND, CHF partners and other actors operational in the targeted locations.
The project has two distinct components: 
1. Treatment of moderate acute malnutrition: Targeting children under 5 and PLW in Hirat and KIS, screened and identified as moderately malnourished. The (MAM) children and PLW will be given a bi-weekly and monthly rations of Acha Mum and supercereal respectively in about 88 health facilities in Hirat and 15 mobile sites in KIS. The TSFP will be implemented by BDN and OHPM and ACF in Hirat and KIS respectively. Additional sites will be established based on an assessment by Partners and WFP if needs arises during the implementation period.
 2. Blanket supplementary feeding programme: The BSFP is planned to revert the trend in stunting (see below under ACF assessment reports) with the provision of nutritious complementary food (Wawa Mum) for all children under five and supercereal for PLW.  The BSFP will be implemented by ACDT who is currently supporting implementation of health and nutrition (including TSFP) services at camp with the financial and in-kind support of UNICEF and WFP. All children and PLW enrolled in the BSFP will receive a food ration of Wawa Mum and supercereal respectively for a minimum of six months.
 Behavior change communication (BCC) activities addressing infant and young children feeding practices, maternal nutrition, hygiene and sanitation will be provided to the entire targeted communities, but focusing on the project&#x2019;s direct beneficiaries and their families.</narrative>
  </description>
